MENU SYSTEM:

The menu system allows the creation of both menu-style and wizard-
style question systems, using the same menu option definitions.

Menus should include <menu.h> and inherit MENU.

Menu options types are:

Value entry (MENU_TYPE_ENTRY) - enter an arbitrary value.
	Can be MENU_TYPE_STRING or MENU_TYPE_INT.
	Can be MENU_TYPE_MULTI_ENTRY.
	INT options can have an associated allowed range.
	Can have default values.

Choice entry (MENU_TYPE_CHOICE) - enter one of a defined list of values.
	Can be MENU_TYPE_STRING or MENU_TYPE_INT.
	Can be MENU_TYPE_MULTI_ENTRY.
	INT options can have an associated allowed range.
	Can have default values.
	Can be either list or condensed style.

Separator (MENU_TYPE_SEP) - text only separator value

Sub-menu (MENU_TYPE_SUBMENU) - submenu of options

Exit (MENU_TYPE_EXIT) - exit choice to leave the menu
	Can either completely exit, or just exit a submenu.

Command (MENU_TYPE_COMMAND) - just calls the callback function as a command.

Edit (MENU_TYPE_EDIT) - Calls the edit daemon like the bboards.

Options can use closures for title, prompt, default value, choices,
validation function, callback function, hidden, and next option (wizard mode).


Regular mode: Starts out with a menu of options with numerical option
              selection.
Wizard mode: Runs through a list of options one at a time, as determined
             by the option's "next" parameter. At end of list, an exit
             type option can be used to exit the wizard, or the wizard
             can drop back into normal menu mode.

Menus always have a submenu defined named "default". This is the menu
that will contain options that are added with no parent. It is displayed
with start_menu() if no start option name is provided.

NOTE: *ALWAYS* use a clone of your menu object! Otherwise, multiple 
      people using it at the same time will step on each other.


Menu Inheritable:

varargs void add_option(string sName, int iType, mixed xTitle,
                        mixed xPrompt, string sParent):
Adds a menu option.
	sName must be unique amongst all the options defined
	for the menu. 

	iType is a bitfield of:
		The following are mutually exclusive:
		MENU_TYPE_SUBMENU
		MENU_TYPE_ENTRY
		MENU_TYPE_CHOICE
		MENU_TYPE_SEP
		MENU_TYPE_EXIT

		The following are for ENTRY and CHOICE only:
		MENU_TYPE_STRING
		MENU_TYPE_INT
		MENU_TYPE_MULTI_ENTRY - keep prompting until <enter>

		The following are for CHOICE only:
		MENU_TYPE_CHOICE_STYLE_LIST - list prompt style
		MENU_TYPE_CHOICE_STYLE_FLAT - condensed prompt style

		The following is for EXIT options only:
		MENU_TYPE_EXIT_STYLE_POP - don't exit menu completely

	xTitle is either a string or closure, and is displayed in menu
	listings and before prompts.

	xPrompt is either a string or closure, and is displayed when
	entering a value only.

	sParent is the name of the submenu (defaults to "default") to
	which this option belongs.

void set_option_title(string sOption, mixed xTitle):
Sets the title for a menu option. May be a closure or a string.	A closure
will be passed the option info mapping.

void set_option_prompt(string sOption, mixed xPrompt):
Sets the prompt for a menu option. May be a closure or a string. A closure
will be passed the option info mapping.

void set_option_default(string sOption, mixed xDefault);
Sets the default value for a menu option. May be a closure or a string.	
A closure will be passed the option info mapping.

void set_option_choices(string sOption, string *asChoices);
Sets the list of allowed values for MENU_TYPE_CHOICE options. May be a
closure or a list of strings. A closure will be passed the option info mapping.

void set_option_validator(string sOption, mixed xValidator);
Sets the validation function for an option. Must be a closure.
	The validation function is passed two arguments: a string value
	and the option info mapping. It should return 0 if the value
	is valid, or a string error message if not.

void set_option_integer_range(string sOption, int iMin, int iMax);
Sets the valid range for an INT type option.

void set_option_callback(string sOption, mixed xCallback);
Sets the callback function for an option. Must be a closure.
	The callback function is passed two arguments: a string value
	and the option info mapping.

void set_option_next(string sOption, mixed xNext);
Sets the next option in line for wizard mode. Can be a string name or
a closure that returns a string.

void set_option_hiden(string sOption, mixed xHidden)
Sets whether the option is visible or not. Can be a closure that returns
an integer.

varargs void start_menu(object oUser, string sMenu):
Starts the menu at option sMenu (usually a submenu type option).

varargs void start_wizard(object oUser, string sOption);
Starts the menu in wizard mode at the specified option.


Examples:

/open/testmenu.c is an example of a way to use the menu options. It can be
started in both normal and wizard mode.

  // Set the title and prompt for the main menu
  set_option_title("default", "Test Menu Title");

  // The function "test_prompt" in this object will be called for the prompt.
  set_option_prompt("default", symbol_function("test_prompt", this_object()));


  // Add a string entry option
  add_option("test1", MENU_TYPE_ENTRY|MENU_TYPE_STRING, "Enter Name");

  // The menu will call the "test_callback" function in this object each time
  // a value is entered for the option.
  set_option_callback("test1", symbol_function("test_callback", this_object()));

  // In wizard mode, go to option test2 after completing this option.
  set_option_next("test1", "test2");


  // Add a string entry option with a set a allowed values that print in list
  // style (numbered selections). The title of the option will be returned
  // from the "test_test2_title" function in this object:
  // 
  // <title>
  //         1) blue
  //         2) red
  //         3) green
  // Enter value: 
  add_option("test2",
	     MENU_TYPE_CHOICE|MENU_TYPE_STRING|MENU_TYPE_CHOICE_STYLE_LIST,
	     symbol_function("test_test2_title", this_object()));

  // The menu will call the "test_callback" function in this object each time
  // a value is entered for the option.
  set_option_callback("test2", symbol_function("test_callback", this_object()));

  // The allowed choices are blue, red, and green
  set_option_choices("test2", ({ "blue", "red", "green" }) );

  // In wizard mode, go to option test3 after completing this option.
  set_option_next("test2", "test3");


  // Add a separator between options test2 and test3
  add_option("testsep", MENU_TYPE_SEP, "-=-=- This Is A Separator -=-=-");


  // Add an integer entry option
  add_option("test3", MENU_TYPE_ENTRY|MENU_TYPE_INT, "Enter Age");
  set_option_callback("test3", symbol_function("test_callback", this_object()));

  // Note how this option chains to an option for a different submenu in wizard
  // mode. This lets you go through ALL of the selections in wizard mode, and
  // then fallback to a default hierarchical menu when all the entries have been made.
  set_option_next("test3", "sub1");


  // Add a submenu off the main menu.
  add_option("testsub", MENU_TYPE_SUBMENU, "Do Some Other Stuff", "What do you want to do?");


  // Add an exit option. This option will exit the menu completely when selected.
  add_option("test4", MENU_TYPE_EXIT, "Exit");


  // Enter a normal string value entry option.
  add_option("sub1", MENU_TYPE_ENTRY|MENU_TYPE_STRING, "Enter Spoob", "Spoob value?", "testsub");
  set_option_callback("sub1", symbol_function("test_callback", this_object()));
  set_option_next("sub1", "subint");
  // Set the default value to "spoobalicious"
  set_option_default("sub1", "spoobalicious");


  // Add an integer type option with an allowed range of 9 to 100, with a default
  // of 42.
  add_option("subint", MENU_TYPE_ENTRY|MENU_TYPE_INT, "Enter Spork", "Spork value?", "testsub");
  set_option_integer_range("subint", 9, 100);
  set_option_default("subint", 42);
  set_option_callback("subint", symbol_function("test_callback", this_object()));
  set_option_next("subint", "sub2");


  // Add a choice type entry using the flat style:
  // 
  // Glorb: [Y/n] 
  add_option("sub2", MENU_TYPE_CHOICE|MENU_TYPE_STRING|MENU_TYPE_CHOICE_STYLE_FLAT,
	     "Glorb.", "Glorb:", "testsub");
  set_option_callback("sub2", symbol_function("test_callback", this_object()));
  set_option_choices("sub2", ({ "y", "n" }) );

  // Note that the default entry for a flat-style choice option gets capitalized
  // when displayed to signify that it is the default.
  set_option_default("sub2", "y");


  // Add a multi-entry string option. The prompt will display based on the number
  // of lines entered.
  add_option("sub3", MENU_TYPE_ENTRY|MENU_TYPE_STRING|MENU_TYPE_MULTI_ENTRY,
	     "Multi-Glorb.", symbol_function("count_prompt", this_object()), "testsub");

  // The callback function will be sent a value of "" when the user hits <enter> to
  // exit the option.
  set_option_callback("sub3", symbol_function("test_callback_multi", this_object()));


  // Add an exit option. This option will exit the submenu and return to the main
  // menu when selected.
  add_option("sub4", MENU_TYPE_EXIT|MENU_TYPE_EXIT_STYLE_POP, "Back To Main Menu", 0, "testsub");
